# Step 3: Calculate Earliest Expiration Date

### Purpose

Determine the earliest valid expiration date across all expiration-related fields and store it as the asset's `calculated_expiration_date`.

### Processing Logic

After fetching the record details, the utility extracts the following fields:

| Source                     | Field                 |
| -------------------------- | --------------------- |
| Asset                      | Asset Expiration Date |
| Usage Rights Records (URR) | End Date              |
| MLR Records                | Expiration Date       |

The utility then creates a collection of all valid dates.

### Example

Retrieved values:

```json
{
  "assetExpirationDate": "2028-12-15",
  "urrEndDates": [
    "2028-10-10",
    "2028-08-20"
  ],
  "mlrExpirationDates": [
    "2028-09-05"
  ]
}
```

Candidate dates:

```text
2028-12-15
2028-10-10
2028-08-20
2028-09-05
```

The utility selects the minimum (earliest) date:

```text
2028-08-20
```

This becomes:

```text
calculated_expiration_date = 2028-08-20
```

### Node.js Implementation

```javascript
const allDates = [
  assetExpirationDate,
  ...urrEndDates,
  ...mlrExpirationDates
]
.filter(Boolean)
.map(date => new Date(date));

const earliestDate = new Date(
  Math.min(...allDates.map(date => date.getTime()))
);
```

### Business Rule

> The earliest available date among Asset Expiration Date, linked Usage Rights Record End Dates, and linked MLR Expiration Dates shall be considered the effective expiration date of the asset.

